The '''60th Primetime Emmy Awards''' were held on Sunday, September 21, 2008, at the newly opened [[Peacock Theater|Nokia Theatre]] in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]] to honor the best in [[United States|U.S.]] [[prime time]] television.<ref>{{cite news|title=Emmys will move to new venue|work=[[USA Today]]|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/television/news/2008-03-11-emmys_N.htm|access-date=March 11, 2008 | date=March 11, 2008}}</ref> The ceremony was hosted by [[Tom Bergeron]] (who was also hosting ''[[America's Funniest Home Videos]]'' and ''[[Dancing with the Stars (American TV series)|Dancing with the Stars]]'', both also on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]], at the time), [[Heidi Klum]], [[Howie Mandel]], [[Jeff Probst]], and [[Ryan Seacrest]] (all were nominated in the debut category—[[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Host for a Reality or Reality-Competition Program|Outstanding Host for a Reality or Reality-Competition Program]]) and televised in the United States on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]. 28 awards were presented.

The nominations were announced on July 17 by [[Kristin Chenoweth]] and [[Neil Patrick Harris]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cdn.emmys.tv/awards/2008pte/60thpte_nomswin.php|title=Noms}}</ref> The [[Creative Arts Emmy Award]]s were held eight days earlier (September 13) at the same venue. The ceremony was hosted by [[Neil Patrick Harris]] and [[Sarah Chalke]].

The telecast was viewed by 12.20 million with a household rating of 8.86/12.79 making it the lowest rated and least viewed ceremony in its televised history.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.worldscreen.com/newscurrent.php?filename=emmys092308.htm |title=World Screen - Home |access-date=2008-10-01 |archive-date=2009-01-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090112230040/http://www.worldscreen.com/newscurrent.php?filename=emmys092308.htm |url-status=dead }}</ref> Many critics cited lackluster performances from the [[#Hosting|five hosts]] as a reason for the huge decline.<ref>[http://www.thrfeed.com/2008/09/emmy-reviews.html The Live Feed; 60th Emmy Awards reviews]</ref> Others pointed to the field of nominees which were dominated by low-rated and sparsely viewed programs, thus making the Emmys widely considered as a bust, which was panned by critics as "... the worst ever, laid a big, fat ratings egg as well ..."<ref>[http://www.broadcastingcable.com/article/CA6599959.html Give Emmys to Craig] from ''Broadcasting and Cable''</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Emmy telecast bombs in ratings and reviews |website=[[Reuters]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200915192229/https://www.reuters.com/article/industryNews/idUSTRE48M1L620080923 |archive-date=2020-09-15 |url-status=live |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/industryNews/idUSTRE48M1L620080923}}</ref>

In 2011, when [[Pop (U.S. TV network)|TV Guide Network]] re-did their list of "25 Biggest TV Blunders", this ceremony was included.

For the first time in a decade, the [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Comedy Series]] was won by the defending champion. ''[[30 Rock]]''

[[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Drama Series|Outstanding Drama Series]] went to [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]] freshmen series ''[[Mad Men]]''. This marked the first series award for a program on a [[Cable television in the United States#Basic cable|basic cable]] station. ''Mad Men'' led all dramas with six major nominations.

This would be the final ceremony to have five nominees per category, most major categories (acting and programs) were expanded to include at least six slots the following year.

